Summary: Introduces the available CSG nodes in Godot.
CSG nodes are the building blocks for Constructive Solid Geometry operations in Godot. The available CSG nodes are:
CSGBox3D
CSGCylinder3D (also supports cone)
CSGSphere3D
CSGTorus3D
CSGPolygon3D
CSGMesh3D
CSGCombiner3D
---CHUNK---
Document: CSG tools features
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/csg_tools.rst
Summary: This section describes the three boolean operations supported by CSG nodes in Godot.
CSG nodes support three kinds of boolean operations:
* Union: Geometry of both primitives is merged, intersecting geometry is removed.
* Intersection: Only intersecting geometry remains, the rest is removed.
* Subtraction: The second shape is subtracted from the first, leaving a dent with its shape.
---CHUNK---
Document: CSG Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/csg_tools.rst
Summary: Explains the CSGPolygon3D node and its extrusion modes.
CSGPolygon3D
The CSGPolygon3D node extrudes a 2D polygon (defined in X, Y coordinates) in the following ways:
- Depth: Extruded back a given amount.
- Spin: Extruded while spinning around its origin.
- Path: Extruded along a Path3D node. This operation is commonly called lofting.
Note: The Path mode must be provided with a Path3D node to work. In the Path node, draw the path and the polygon in CSGPolygon3D will extrude along the given path.
---CHUNK---
Document: CSG Tools
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/csg_tools.rst
Summary: This section explains the requirements for using custom meshes with CSGMesh3D, focusing on the concept of manifold geometry.

Custom meshes can be used for CSGMesh3D as long as the mesh is manifold. The mesh can be modeled in other software and imported into Godot. Multiple materials are supported.

For a mesh to be used as a CSG mesh, it is required to:
* be closed
* have each edge connect to only two faces
* have volume

And it is recommended to avoid:
* negative volume
* self-intersection
* interior faces

Godot uses the manifold library to implement CSG meshes. The technical definition of "manifold" used by Godot is the following, adapted from that library's definition of "manifold":

Every edge of every triangle must contain the same two vertices (by index) as exactly one other triangle edge, and the start and end vertices must switch places between these two edges. The triangle vertices must appear in clockwise order when viewed from the outside of the Godot Engine manifold mesh.
---CHUNK---
